  "opinion": "As a 23-year-old self-employed hairdresser in Washington DC, I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly for work and connecting with clients, so dealing with fake content is a practical concern for me. My high conscientiousness means I value accuracy and reliability, especially when it affects my business reputation, and my high openness makes me curious but cautious about new information. I see fake content as a real problem that can mislead people and damage trust, whether it's false reviews about salons, misleading health tips, or political misinformation that affects our community. To manage it, I rely on a few straightforward strategies. First, I always check the source before sharing anything—looking at who posted it and if it's from a credible organization or person I know. For example, if I see a viral post about a new hair product, I'll search for reviews from trusted beauty bloggers or check the brand's official page. Second, I use fact-checking websites like Snopes or PolitiFact when something seems off, especially with news stories that pop up in my feed. Third, I'm careful about what I engage with; I avoid spreading unverified claims and instead promote accurate content from reliable sources, like sharing posts from reputable salons or industry experts. My moderate extraversion means I'm not overly active online, but I do value genuine interactions, so I encourage friends and clients to question what they see and talk about it openly. As an atheist with no strong religious influences, I base my views on evidence and reason, which helps me stay skeptical of sensational claims. Ultimately, managing fake content is about being proactive and responsible—taking a moment to verify before reacting, which protects my business and helps maintain a trustworthy online environment for everyone.",
